text.section:
The board may refuse to issue a license, or may suspend, revoke, impose probationary conditions upon, impose an administrative fine upon, or issue a written reprimand against the holder of a license to practice ophthalmic dispensing or an apprentice license if the applicant or licensee has:
Committed a dishonest or corrupt act. If the act is a crime, conviction in a criminal proceeding shall not be a condition precedent to disciplinary action. Upon conviction of the crime, the judgment and sentence are presumptive evidence of guilt at the ensuing disciplinary hearing of the licensee. Conviction includes all instances in which a plea of no contest is the basis of the conviction;
Committed any unfair, false, misleading, or deceptive act or practice;
Been incompetent or negligent in the practice of ophthalmic dispensing;
Failed to comply with a lawful order of the board;
Aided or abetted another person in falsely procuring or attempting to procure a license;
Aided or abetted an unlicensed person in activities which violate KRS 326.030 and which are not otherwise exempted from the provisions of this chapter;
Exhibited chronic or persistent inebriety or addiction to a drug habit, to an extent that disqualifies the applicant or the licensee from practicing with safety to the public;
Committed fraud or deception in the application or in the examination for the license; or
Violated any provisions of this chapter or administrative regulations promulgated in accordance with this chapter.
